OL,3,CScientists use lab-grown 'mini guts'
OL,4,Cto study Crohn's disease
OL,6,F"They've essentially given us pieces
OL,7,Fof their bowel to help with our
OL,8,Fresearch."
OL,10,FBy using the mini organs, researchers
OL,11,Fdiscovered that switches which modify
OL,12,FDNA in gut cells play an important
OL,13,Frole in the disease and how it
OL,14,Fpresents in patients.
OL,16,FThese switches are attached to DNA
OL,17,Fthat turn genes on and off ` or turn
OL,18,Ftheir activity up or down ` leaving
OL,19,Fthe DNA itself intact, but changing
OL,20,Fthe way a cell functions.
